          "body": "Verses 8-12 are a forensic masterstroke. Elihu quotes Job back to himself verbatim before issuing his verdict, preventing the charge of misrepresentation. Job's three claims: (1) 'I am pure, without transgression' (33:9; cf. Job 9:21; 10:7); (2) God 'invents pretexts against me' and 'counts me as His enemy' (33:10; cf. Job 13:24); (3) 'He puts my feet in the stocks; He watches all my paths' (33:11; cf. Job 13:27). These are not paraphrases — they are near-verbatim citations from Job's earlier speeches. Elihu's single-sentence verdict in verse 12 is therefore irrefutable on its own terms: 'You are not right in this, for God is greater than man.' The argument is not 'you sinned, therefore God afflicts you' — it is something subtler: the fundamental asymmetry between Creator and creature makes the categories Job is deploying (legal innocence, divine hostility, unjust surveillance) inapplicable. A man cannot sue his Maker on terms the Maker must accept. This is not the answer that fully satisfies — God's own speeches from the whirlwind will press the same point far more powerfully (chapters 38-41) — but Elihu locates the right fault-line: the problem is not God's injustice but Job's category error."
