          "body": "The second communicative mode is physical suffering, which Elihu describes with clinical precision in verses 19-22. 'Man is also chastened with pain on his bed, and with unceasing complaint in his bones' (33:19) — the word 'chastened' (yakhach) is the same word used in Proverbs 3:12 ('the LORD disciplines the one He loves') and in Job 5:17 (Eliphaz's earlier, less developed version of the same insight). The progression is merciless in its realism: pain produces anorexia (33:20), the flesh wastes until the bones are visible (33:21), and 'his soul draws near to the pit, and his life to those who bring death' (33:22). This is not punishment as retribution — the narrative framework of the book has already established that Job's suffering is not caused by his sin (1:1-2:10). Rather, Elihu is arguing that suffering, whatever its ultimate cause, functions as a medium of divine speech. The message of the wasting body is the same as the message of the nocturnal vision: you are not in control, your life is not your own, and pride must yield. When the body fails, the illusion of self-sufficiency fails with it. Suffering strips the man of everything he trusted except God."
